05556nam a22009615i 9780812202526DE-B159720220424125308.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220424t20122003pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)1013938577  a(OCoLC)1037979778  a(OCoLC)1041926463  a(OCoLC)1045525813  a(OCoLC)1046612443  a(OCoLC)1047007934  a97808122025267 a10.9783/97808122025262doi  a(DE-B1597)449110  a(OCoLC)979580237  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBP194.5.T4bK67 2003eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a297.3 62211 aKorom, Frank J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aHosay Trinidad :bMuharram Performances in an Indo-Caribbean Diaspora /cFrank J. Korom. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2012] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (320 p.) :b31 illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tA Note on Orthography -- tIntroduction -- t1 Orientations and Overview -- t2 Muharram Rituals in Iran:Past and Present -- t3 The Passage of Rites to South Asia -- t4 Onward to the Caribbean -- t5 Building the Tadjah, Constructing Community -- t6 Conclusion: Maintenance and Transformation via Cultural Creolization -- tEpilogue -- tNotes -- tGlossary -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe multivocalic rite known as Hosay in the Caribbean developed out of earlier practices originating in Iraq and Iran which diffused to Trinidad by way of South Asian indentured laborers brought to the Caribbean by the British from the mid-1800s to the early decades of the twentieth century. The rituals are important as a Shi'i religious observance, but they also are emblems of ethnic and national identity for Indo-Trinidadians. Frank Korom investigates the essential role of Hosay in the performance of multiple identities by historically and ethnographically situating the event in Middle Eastern, South Asian, and Caribbean contexts. Hosay Trinidad: Muharram Performances in an Indo-Caribbean Diaspora is the first detailed historical and ethnographic study of Islamic muharram rituals performed on the island of Trinidad.Korom's central argument is that the annual rite is a polyphonic discourse that is best understood by employing multiple levels of interpretation. On the symbolic level the observance provides esoteric meaning to a small community of Indo-Trinidadian Muslims. On another level, it is perceived to be representative of "transplanted" Indian culture as a whole. Finally, the rituals are becoming emblematic of Trinidad's polyethnic population. Addressing strategies used to resist integration and assimilation, Hosay Trinidad is engaged with theories concerning the notion of cultural creolization in the Caribbean as well as in the general study of global diasporas.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aMuslimsvTrinidad and Tobago. 0aMuslimszTrinidad and Tobago. 0aSOCIAL SCIENCEvAnthropologyvCultural. 0aShi`ahvCustoms and practices. 0aShi`ahvTrinidad and Tobago. 0aShīʿahxCustoms and practices. 0aShīʿahzTrinidad and Tobago. 0aShīʻahxCustoms and practices. 0aShīʻahzTrinidad and Tobago. 0aTenth of Muḥarram. 0aTenth of Muḥarram. 4aFolklore. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aFolklore.  aLinguistics.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Social Sciencesz978311041361808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/9780812202526